{"title_page": "The Next Day", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 album by David Bowie}}\n{{About|the David Bowie album|the album's titular song|The Next Day (song)}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Next Day\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| cover      = David Bowie - The Next Day.png\n| released   = {{Start date|2013|3|8|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = May 2011 \u2013 February 2013\n| studio     = The Magic Shop, Human Worldwide, [[Manhattan]], NY\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[art rock]]}}\n| length     = 53:17\n| label      = {{hlist|ISO|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|David Bowie|[[Tony Visconti]]}}\n| prev_title = [[A Reality Tour (album)|A Reality Tour]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[Nothing Has Changed]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n| misc       = {{Singles\n  | name        = The Next Day\n  | type        = studio\n  | single1     = [[Where Are We Now?]]\n  | single1date = 8 January 2013\n  | single2     = [[The Stars (Are Out Tonight)]]\n  | single2date = 26 February 2013\n  | single3     = [[The Next Day (song)|The Next Day]]\n  | single3date = 17 June 2013\n  | single4     = [[Valentine's Day (David Bowie song)|Valentine's Day]]\n  | single4date = 19 August 2013\n  | single5     = [[Love Is Lost]]\n  | single5date = 28 October 2013\n  }}\n}}\n'''''The Next Day''''' is the 24th and penultimate studio album by English musician [[David Bowie]], released on 8 March 2013 on his ISO Records label, under exclusive licence to [[Columbia Records]]. Co-produced by Bowie and longtime collaborator [[Tony Visconti]], the album was recorded in secret at The Magic Shop and Human Worldwide Studios in New York City between 2011 and 2013. It is primarily a [[Rock music|rock]] album, featuring elements of [[art rock]]. The cover art is an adapted version of his 1977 album ''[[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie album)|\"Heroes\"]]'', featuring a white square with the album's title obscuring his face. It was announced on Bowie's 66th birthday, 8 January 2013.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/08/david-bowie-new-album-single |title=David Bowie to release new album, with surprise single out now |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |location=London, England |date=8 January 2013 |accessdate=8 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002210049/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/08/david-bowie-new-album-single |archive-date=2 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bowie's website was updated with the video for the lead single, \"[[Where Are We Now?]]\", and the single was immediately made available for purchase on the [[iTunes Store]].\n\nIt was Bowie's first album of new material in ten years, since 2003's ''[[Reality (David Bowie album)|Reality]]'', and surprised fans and media who believed he had retired.<ref>{{Cite newspaper | first=Neil | last=McCormick | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/9787215/David-Bowies-Where-Are-We-Now-first-review.html | title=David Bowie's Where Are We Now? \u2013 first review | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] | location=London, England | date=8 January 2013 | accessdate=20 November 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114135109/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/9787215/David-Bowies-Where-Are-We-Now-first-review.html | archive-date=14 January 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref> The album was streamed in its entirety on [[iTunes]] days before its official release.<ref>{{cite web |title=Listen to the Next Day on iTunes now! |url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151270031222665&set=a.424610777664.193516.30899502664&type=1&theater |work=David Bowie (Official) |publisher=Facebook |accessdate=1 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918220742/https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151270031222665&set=a.424610777664.193516.30899502664&type=1&theater |archive-date=18 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''The Next Day Extra'', an additional disc featuring four more tracks, and remixes of songs from the original album, was released in November.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/3-disc-next-day-extra-due-november-release-52051 |title=Next Day extra due november |publisher=Davidbowie.com |accessdate=28 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130930070812/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/3-disc-next-day-extra-due-november-release-52051 |archive-date=30 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''The Next Day'' was met with critical acclaim, and earned Bowie his first number-one album in the United Kingdom since 1993's ''[[Black Tie White Noise]]''.<ref name=Guardian0313>{{Cite news|first=Caspar Llewellyn|last=Smith|title=David Bowie tops albums chart for first time in 20 years|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/mar/18/bowie-next-day-number-one|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|location=London, England|date=18 March 2013|accessdate=17 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110125422/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/mar/18/bowie-next-day-number-one|archive-date=10 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was ranked as the second best album of 2013 (in a tie with [[Blue October]]'s ''[[Sway (Blue October album)|Sway]]'') by German music magazine ''[[:de:Kulturnews|Kulturnews]]'' and was also nominated for the 2013 [[Mercury Prize]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24050986|title=David Bowie, Jake Bugg and Laura Mvula in Mercury race|website=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|location=London, England|date=11 September 2013|accessdate=12 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110171936/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-24050986|archive-date=10 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The album was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2014 Grammy Awards]] and for MasterCard British Album of the Year at the [[2014 Brit Awards]].\n\nThe album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.\n\n==Recording==\nRecording of the album took place at The Magic Shop and Human Worldwide Studios in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"album notes\"/> Bowie and producer [[Tony Visconti]] worked in secret alongside long-term engineer [[Mario J. McNulty]], recording the album over a two-year period.<ref name=RS13>{{cite web |title=David Bowie Worked in Secret on Comeback LP for Two Years |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/david-bowie-worked-in-secret-on-comeback-lp-for-two-years-20130109?link=mostpopular5 |accessdate=10 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113044300/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/david-bowie-worked-in-secret-on-comeback-lp-for-two-years-20130109?link=mostpopular5 |archive-date=13 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The recording sessions were sporadic, and Visconti estimated that only three full months were spent demoing and recording material. Visconti recalled that the album began with a one-week recording session:\n{{quote|Sterling Campbell was on drums, I was on bass, David was on keyboards, Gerry Leonard was on guitar. By the end of five days we had demoed up a dozen songs. Just structures. No lyrics, no melodies and all working titles. This is how everything begins with him. Then he took them home and we didn't hear another thing from him for four months.<ref name=OC13>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopmusic/9797475/David-Bowie-is-healthy-and-may-even-sing-in-public-again-says-Tony-Visconti.html |title=David Bowie is healthy and may even sing in public again, says Tony Visconti |accessdate=6 September 2014 |first=Cole |last=Moreton |date=13 January 2013 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217214403/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopmusic/9797475/David-Bowie-is-healthy-and-may-even-sing-in-public-again-says-Tony-Visconti.html |archive-date=17 February 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\nBowie would disappear with the music \"to make sure he was on the right track\", then bring the band back together to take the next step in recording when he was ready. Visconti described the recording sessions as \"intense\", but they stuck to regular hours. \"The last time we did all-nighters was ''[[Young Americans (album)|Young Americans]]''\".<ref name=OC13/>\n\nDuring breaks from the studio, Visconti would walk the streets of New York listening to music from ''The Next Day'' on his earphones:<ref name=RS13/> \"I was walking around New York with my headphones on, looking at all the people with Bowie T-shirts on\u2014they are ubiquitous here\u2014thinking, 'Boy, if you only knew what I'm listening to at the moment.'\"<ref name=OC13/>\n\nDespite the statement that no guest artists were used to record the album,<ref name=HR13>{{cite news |title=David Bowie Producer Talks New Music, Health Scare: 'Album Is Physical Evidence That He's Fine' (Q&A) |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/david-bowie-producer-new-album-411233 |accessdate=11 January 2013 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Shirley |last=Halperin |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130114022155/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/david-bowie-producer-new-album-411233 |archive-date=14 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bowie did use some of the musicians he's worked with in the past, including [[Earl Slick]], who recorded his parts for the album in July 2012.<ref name=NMEES>{{cite web |title=David Bowie's guitarist Earl Slick: 'We want him to tour' |url=http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/68115 |accessdate=11 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113073211/http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/68115 |archive-date=13 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Gail Ann Dorsey]] (bass guitar) and [[Sterling Campbell]] (drums), who had both worked with Bowie since the 1990s, also contributed to the album.<ref name=Slick>{{cite web |title=Exclusive: Guitarist Earl Slick Reveals New David Bowie Album Details |url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/earl-slick-david-bowie-new-album-interview/ |accessdate=10 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112023620/http://ultimateclassicrock.com/earl-slick-david-bowie-new-album-interview/ |archive-date=12 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Dorsey also recorded vocals for the song \"If You Can See Me\".<ref name=Times>{{cite news |title=Visconti's Guide to Bowie's new album |work=The Times UK |date=16 January 2013}}</ref> Drummer Zachary Alford <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/258947-Zachary-Alford |title=Discogs \u2013 ''Zachary Alford''  |access-date=26 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129164710/https://www.discogs.com/artist/258947-Zachary-Alford |archive-date=29 November 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and guitarists Gerry Leonard and [[David Torn]] were hired for the sessions and Slick revealed that Visconti also contributed bass.<ref name=Slick/> Saxophonist Steve Elson, who had worked with Bowie since the 1980s, also plays on the album.<ref name=preview>{{cite news |last=Greene |first=Andrew |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/david-bowies-the-next-day-album-a-track-by-track-preview-20130115 |title=David Bowie's 'The Next' Day' Album: A Track-by-Track Preview |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=15 January 2013 |accessdate=19 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118043842/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/david-bowies-the-next-day-album-a-track-by-track-preview-20130115 |archive-date=18 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> A story that [[Robert Fripp]], who previously has worked with Bowie in the studio, was invited to play on the album but could not due to other commitments<ref name=GUK13>{{Cite journal | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/12/david-bowie-how-made-next-day | title=The inside story of how David Bowie made The Next Day | journal=[[The Guardian]] | date=11 January 2013 | accessdate=19 June 2013 | last=Petridis | first=Alexis | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207151456/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/12/david-bowie-how-made-next-day | archive-date=7 December 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> was denied by Fripp, who said, \"I haven't spoken to David for a while and I wasn't approached [to take part in the album]\", adding \"I'm not angry at all. No one is hurt, I'm not upset, just keen for clarity.\"<ref name=GCUK13x>{{Cite journal | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/18/robert-fripp-david-bowie-album | title=Robert Fripp: 'I didn't turn down chance to play on David Bowie album' | last=Petridis | first=Alexis | date=18 January 2013 | accessdate=15 July 2013 | journal=The Guardian | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229051317/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jan/18/robert-fripp-david-bowie-album | archive-date=29 December 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Secrecy===\nBowie took great pains to keep the recording of the album secret, requiring people involved in the recording to sign [[Non-disclosure agreement|NDA]]s. Bowie had to change recording studios after one day when someone at the studio disclosed that Bowie was recording there. He moved to the studio The Magic Shop, which ran the studio with a skeleton crew of only one or two employees on days when Bowie was there. [[Columbia Records]]'s UK PR firm learned of the project only a few days before the album was released.<ref name=GUK13 />\n\nCanadian band [[Metric (band)|Metric]] almost uncovered the secret recording sessions when they arrived at Magic Shop recording studios unannounced in 2011, and Bowie saxophonist Steve Elson said he was tempted to reveal all.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/David-Bowies-cover-almost-blown/tabid/418/articleID/288566/Default.aspx |work=3 News NZ |title=David Bowie's cover almost blown |date=1 March 2013 |access-date=28 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702181949/http://www.3news.co.nz/David-Bowies-cover-almost-blown/tabid/418/articleID/288566/Default.aspx |archive-date=2 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/metric-almost-walked-secret-david-bowie-recording-session-162400420.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130412055557/http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/metric-almost-walked-secret-david-bowie-recording-session-162400420.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 April 2013 |work=Yahoo |title=Metric almost walked into secret David Bowie recording session |date=1 March 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n''The Next Day'' is a [[Rock music|rock]] album,<ref name=\"quietus-review\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/music_box/2013/03/david_bowie_s_the_next_day_reviewed.html | title=The Next Day | work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] | accessdate=28 December 2015 | author=Dayal, Geeta | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112062620/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/music_box/2013/03/david_bowie_s_the_next_day_reviewed.html | archive-date=12 January 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.timeout.com/london/music/david-bowie-the-next-day-album-review | title=David Bowie \u2013 'The Next Day' album review | work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] | date=26 February 2013 | accessdate=28 December 2015 | author=Keens, Oliver | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915021950/http://www.timeout.com/london/music/david-bowie-the-next-day-album-review | archive-date=15 September 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"seasonincrime-guard\"/> mainly featuring [[art rock]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/david-bowie/16363 | title=David Bowie \u2013 'Blackstar' Review: The NME Verdict | work=[[NME]] | date=3 January 2016 | accessdate=7 January 2016 | author=Richards, Sam | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304235955/http://www.nme.com/reviews/david-bowie/16363 | archive-date=4 March 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Tony Visconti told the ''NME'' that ''The Next Day'' \"is quite a rock album\"<ref name=Visconti/> and [[Alexis Petridis]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' considered the record \"a straightforward rock album.\"<ref name=\"seasonincrime-guard\">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/oct/12/david-bowie-sue-in-a-season-of-crime-review | title=David Bowie: Sue (or In a Season of Crime) \u2013 review | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=12 October 2014 | accessdate=28 November 2015 | author=Petridis, Alexis | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127133521/http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/oct/12/david-bowie-sue-in-a-season-of-crime-review | archive-date=27 November 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/nov/19/david-bowie-blackstar-review-as-a-taster-for-the-forthcoming-album-it-works-perfectly | title=David Bowie: Blackstar review \u2013 'As a taster for the forthcoming album, it works perfectly' | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=19 November 2015 | accessdate=28 November 2015 | author=Petridis, Alex | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127215648/http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/nov/19/david-bowie-blackstar-review-as-a-taster-for-the-forthcoming-album-it-works-perfectly | archive-date=27 November 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe first single was the ballad \"[[Where Are We Now?]]\", a track which Visconti described as \"the only track on the album that goes this much inward for him\".<ref name=Visconti>[http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/68076 Bowie producer Tony Visconti promises 'rock' sound on new album]. NME. 9 January 2013. Retrieved 9 January 2013.</ref> Visconti suggested that Bowie chose \"Where Are We Now?\" as the opening single because \"people had to deal with the shock that he was back [after a 10-year absence]\" and that the introspective nature of the song made it an appropriate choice. The song reached No.6 in the UK charts. <ref name=HR13/> Opening lyrics for \"Where Are We Now\" reflectively recall the name of a train station (plaza) and a street in west Berlin, where Bowie once lived. A video accompanying the single includes props such as a dismantled photo frame lying discarded on the floor in the opening shot, a large ear in the background, and a two-headed soft doll with the torn faces of Bowie and a voiceless counterpart \"pasted\" onto it in. Lyrics also include the phrase \"the moment you know you know, you know\".\n\n\"[[The Stars (Are Out Tonight)]]\" was released as the second single from the album on 26 February 2013. A music video in the form of a short film was premiered the previous day.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/stars-are-out-tonight-video-exclusive-50561 |work=davidbowie.com |title=The Stars (Are Out Tonight) video exclusive |date=25 February 2013 |access-date=26 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301050934/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/stars-are-out-tonight-video-exclusive-50561 |archive-date=1 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The song received moderate airplay on [[BBC Radio 2]] and 106.9FM WHCR, peaking at number 102 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nVisconti, who accepted an interviewer's suggestion that he was Bowie's \"voice on earth\", commented on the album to the international press and provided insights into the individual tracks.<ref name=Times/> The songs cover a wide spread of subjects and are largely observational: most probe the mind-sets of different individuals.<ref name=Times/> \"[[Valentine's Day (David Bowie song)|Valentine's Day]]\" is about a high school shooter.<ref name=Times/> \"I'd Rather Be High\" related the story of a Second World War soldier.<ref name=Times/> Visconti described the material as \"extremely strong and beautiful\". He added \"if people are looking for classic Bowie they'll find it on this album, if they're looking for innovative Bowie, new directions, they're going to find that on this album too.\"<ref name=Visconti/> Visconti commented that 29 tracks were recorded for the album and suggested that some of the material left out of ''The Next Day'' could appear on a subsequent record. Visconti speculated that Bowie could return to the studio to produce a new album later in 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Bowie-producer-hints-at-more-albums/tabid/418/articleID/282918/Default.aspx |work=3 News NZ |title=Bowie producer hints at more albums |date=14 January 2013 |access-date=13 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702184331/http://www.3news.co.nz/Bowie-producer-hints-at-more-albums/tabid/418/articleID/282918/Default.aspx |archive-date=2 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> but this did not happen.\n\n==Artwork==\nThe [[cover art]] for the album is an adapted version of Bowie's 1977 album, ''[[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie album)|\"Heroes\"]]'', with a white square with the album's title obscuring Bowie's face.<ref name=bbcnews>{{cite news |title=David Bowie releases first single in a decade |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20943160 |publisher=[[BBC Online]] |accessdate=8 January 2013 |date=8 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108173556/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20943160 |archive-date=8 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Designed by [[Jonathan Barnbrook]], who also designed packaging for ''[[Heathen (David Bowie album)|Heathen]]'' and ''Reality'' and follow-up ''[[Blackstar (album)|Blackstar]]'', the obscuring of the photograph connotes \"forgetting or obliterating the past\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://virusfonts.com/news/2013/01/david-bowie-the-next-day-that-album-cover-design/ |title=David Bowie: The Next Day. That album cover design (Barnbrook Design &#124; VirusFonts &#124; Blog) |publisher=VirusFonts |date=8 January 2013 |accessdate=9 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6F833nukC?url=http://virusfonts.com/news/2013/01/david-bowie-the-next-day-that-album-cover-design/ |archivedate=15 March 2013  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barnbrook.net/davidbowie3.html |title=David Bowie: Cover art for Reality |publisher=Barnbrook |accessdate=11 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511223337/http://www.barnbrook.net/davidbowie3.html |archivedate=11 May 2013  }}</ref> The original cover image was shot by Masayoshi Sukita.<ref>{{cite web |author=jeanmendoza |url=http://www.lomography.com/magazine/lifestyle/2011/12/19/masayoshi-sukita-heroes |title=Masayoshi Sukita: Heroes |publisher=Lomography |date=19 December 2011 |accessdate=1 January 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6F8334P6B?url=http://www.lomography.com/magazine/lifestyle/2011/12/19/masayoshi-sukita-heroes |archive-date=15 March 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barnbrook explained the cover, saying: \"If you are going to subvert an album by David Bowie there are many to choose from but this is one of his most revered, it had to be an image that would really jar if it were subverted in some way and we thought ''\"Heroes\"'' worked best on all counts.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.3news.co.nz/David-Bowie-artist-defends-album-cover/tabid/418/articleID/282545/Default.aspx |work=3 News NZ |title=David Bowie artist defends album cover |date=10 January 2013 |access-date=9 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216190807/http://www.3news.co.nz/David-Bowie-artist-defends-album-cover/tabid/418/articleID/282545/Default.aspx |archive-date=16 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A [[viral marketing]] campaign was launched to promote the album on 15 February 2013. The campaign grew out of the concept behind the album cover, taking seemingly ordinary images and subverting them through the addition of a white square.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/us-hit-wave-mysterious-posters-and-stencilling-50411 |title=US hit by wave of mysterious posters and stencilling |publisher=davidbowie.com |date=15 February 2013 |access-date=16 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130324121845/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/us-hit-wave-mysterious-posters-and-stencilling-50411 |archive-date=24 March 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|ADM = 8.1/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/5270/David-Bowie-The-Next-Day.aspx |title=The Next Day by David Bowie reviews |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=30 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230092512/http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/5270/David-Bowie-The-Next-Day.aspx |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|MC = 81/100<ref name=mc>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-next-day/david-bowie |title=Reviews for The Next Day by David Bowie |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=15 March 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Gfksrn2U?url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-next-day/david-bowie |archive-date=17 May 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=the-next-day-mw0002477437 |pure_url=yes}} |title=The Next Day \u2013 David Bowie |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n|rev2score = A\u2212<ref name=Club>{{cite web |last=Heller |first=Jason |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/david-bowie-the-next-day,93543/ |title=David Bowie: The Next Day |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=12 March 2013 |accessdate=21 March 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6GfzXFCta?url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/david-bowie-the-next-day,93543/ |archive-date=17 May 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=telegraph1>{{cite news |last=McCormick |first=Neil |authorlink=Neil McCormick |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/cdreviews/9888192/David-Bowie-The-Next-Day-album-review.html |title=David Bowie, The Next Day, album review |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 February 2013 |accessdate=25 February 2013 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225200329/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/cdreviews/9888192/David-Bowie-The-Next-Day-album-review.html |archive-date=25 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev4score = B<ref>{{cite journal |last=Anderson |first=Kyle |url=http://ew.com/article/2013/03/20/next-day/ |title=The Next Day |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=20 March 2013 |accessdate=20 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205045436/http://ew.com/article/2013/03/20/next-day/ |archive-date=5 February 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n|rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Petridis |first=Alexis |authorlink=Alexis Petridis |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/feb/25/david-bowie-next-day-review |title=David Bowie: The Next Day \u2013 review |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 February 2013 |accessdate=28 February 2013 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031054041/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/feb/25/david-bowie-next-day-review |archive-date=31 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n|rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=independent1>{{cite news|last=Gill |first=Andy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/david-bowie-album-review--track-by-track-the-starman-pulls-off-the-greatest-comeback-album-in-rocknroll-history-with-the-next-day-8510608.html |title=David Bowie album review \u2013 track by track: The Starman pulls off the greatest comeback album in rock'n'roll history with The Next Day |work=[[The Independent]] |date=25 February 2013 |accessdate=25 February 2013 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227094406/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/david-bowie-album-review--track-by-track-the-starman-pulls-off-the-greatest-comeback-album-in-rocknroll-history-with-the-next-day-8510608.html |archivedate=27 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[NME]]''\n|rev7score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal |last=Jones |first=Lucy |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/album/reviews-david-bowie-14183 |title=David Bowie \u2013 The Next Day Album Review |journal=[[NME]] |date=4 March 2013 |accessdate=4 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234814/http://www.nme.com/reviews/david-bowie/14183 |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n|rev8Score = 7.6/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Dombal |first=Ryan |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17855-david-bowie-the-next-day/ |title=David Bowie: The Next Day |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=11 March 2013 |accessdate=11 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906025154/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17855-david-bowie-the-next-day/ |archive-date=6 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Sheffield |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-next-day-20130228 |title=The Next Day |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=28 February 2013 |accessdate=28 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921184057/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/the-next-day-20130228 |archive-date=21 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|rev10score = 5/10<ref name=SPIN>{{cite web |last=Soto |first=Alfred |url=http://www.spin.com/2013/03/david-bowie-the-next-day-columbia-iso/ |title=David Bowie, 'The Next Day' (Columbia/Iso) |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=4 March 2013 |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151028143445/http://www.spin.com/2013/03/david-bowie-the-next-day-columbia-iso/ |archive-date=28 October 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n''The Next Day'' received acclaim from music critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average score out of 100 to reviews and ratings from mainstream critics, the album has received a metascore of 81, based on 44 reviews.<ref name=mc/> Neil McCormick, writing in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', gave the album a five-star review, calling it a \"bold, beautiful and baffling electric bolt through its own mythos\".<ref name=telegraph1/> Andy Gill, in another five-star review for ''[[The Independent]]'', praised the album as \"the greatest comeback album in rock'n'roll history\", adding that the work is \"as good as anything he's made\".<ref name=independent1/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' awarded the album four stars, deeming it \"thought-provoking, strange and filled with great songs\".<ref name=guardian/> ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out London]]'' gave the album a positive notice, praising it as an \"intelligent, memorable and even a little provocative\" addition to Bowie's discography.<ref name=timeout>{{cite web |url=http://now-here-this.timeout.com/2013/02/26/our-verdict-on-david-bowies-the-next-day/ |title=Our verdict on David Bowie's 'The Next Day' |publisher=Time Out London |date=26 February 2013 |accessdate=26 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228191115/http://now-here-this.timeout.com/2013/02/26/our-verdict-on-david-bowies-the-next-day/ |archive-date=28 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a review for [[BBC Music]], Jude Clarke wrote that ''The Next Day'' \"is a triumphant, almost defiant, return. Innovative, dark, bold and creative, it's an album only David Bowie could make\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Jude |last=Clarke |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/rnpn |title=A triumphant, almost defiant, return \u2013 innovative, dark, bold and creative |publisher=BBC |date=26 February 2013 |accessdate=26 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301050406/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/rnpn |archive-date=1 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a review rated 8 out of 10, ''[[NME]]'' said that \"rather than reinventing Bowie, [''The Next Day''] absorbs his past and moves it on\".<ref name=NME>{{cite web |first=Emily |last=Mackay |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/david-bowie/14183 |title=David Bowie \u2013 The Next Day |work=[[NME]] |publisher=[[IPC Media]] |date=4 March 2013 |accessdate=5 March 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6GfkwWDrx?url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/david-bowie/14183 |archive-date=17 May 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Quietus]]'' wrote a positive review and concluded: \"so more than half the album is fantastic, and the rest is very, very strong.\"<ref name=\"quietus-review\">{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Roberts |url=http://thequietus.com/articles/11500-david-bowie-the-next-day-review |title=Great Dame: David Bowie's The Next Day Reviewed |publisher=The Quietus |date=26 February 2013 |accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> At ''[[Q magazine|Q]]'', Andrew Harrison evoked that the release \"feels like a dam bursting\", and this is because the album \"is a loud, thrilling, steamrollingly confident rock and roll album full of noise, energy, and words that [...] if as cryptic as ever they were [...] sound like they desperately need to be sung.\"<ref name=q>{{cite journal|title=Speed of Life: David Bowie \u2013 ''The Next Day''|last=Harrison|first=Andrew|date=April 2013|journal=Q|issue=321|pages=92\u201393|url=http://www.qthemusic.com/|accessdate=29 May 2013|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BhwAnF7h?url=http://www.qthemusic.com/|archive-date=26 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the few negative reviews to emerge from the United Kingdom was in ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal | journal=[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]] | first=Mark | last=Fisher |date=May 2013 }}</ref> Mark Fisher called ''The Next Day'' an album of \"quotidian mediocrity\", saying it was entirely undeserving of its wide acclaim and that the \"wave of hyperbole it generated point[ed] to a wider malaise in contemporary music\" because it proved that anything of low artistic merit could achieve success via \"artfully timed PR\".\n\nReviews in the United States were mainly positive. ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the album \"Bowie's twilight masterpiece\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/america-unites-praise-next-day-50941 |title=America unites in praise of The Next Day |date=14 March 2013 |accessdate=21 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318120853/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/america-unites-praise-next-day-50941 |archive-date=18 March 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> while ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s reviewer wrote: \"No matter where Bowie takes the music \u2013 and there are some moments where it seems headed to some off-putting territory \u2013 he finds a melodic hook to swing on \u2026 This alchemy is almost magical.\"<ref name=\"Billboard review\">{{cite web |last=Gallo |first=Phil |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1549959/david-bowie-the-next-day-track-by-track-review |title=David Bowie, 'The Next Day': Track-By-Track Review |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=27 February 2013 |accessdate=3 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922235837/http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/1549959/david-bowie-the-next-day-track-by-track-review |archive-date=22 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the record four out of four stars and called it a \"glorious homecoming\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/03/10/david-bowie-next-day-album-review/1969723/ |title=David Bowie leaps boldly, nimbly into 'The Next Day' |date=11 March 2013 |accessdate=21 March 2013 |work=USA Today |first1=Edna |last1=Gundersen |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130324052417/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/03/10/david-bowie-next-day-album-review/1969723/ |archive-date=24 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' labelled the work a \"stunning, resonant piece of expression\".<ref name=\"Club\"/> [[CBS News]] even went as far as calling the album \"Bowie's strongest work to date\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-207_162-57573726/david-bowie-reemerges-with-first-album-in-a-decade/ |title=David Bowie reemerges with first album in a decade |date=12 March 2013 |accessdate=21 March 2013 |work=CBS News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318103326/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-207_162-57573726/david-bowie-reemerges-with-first-album-in-a-decade/ |archive-date=18 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' criticised some of the songs:   \n\"The collision of rhetoric and intentions result in both colorless abstractions like piano ballad and first single \"Where Are We Now,\" and grand melodrama like \"You Feel So Lonely You Could Die,\" which ends with the same drum taps used in \"[[Five Years (David Bowie song)|Five Years]]\".\"<ref name=SPIN/> The album was included in the 2014 revised edition of the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=2014 |publisher=Universe|isbn=978-0-7893-2074-2}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''The Next Day'' debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]], selling 94,048 copies in its first week. It was Bowie's ninth number-one album in the United Kingdom, and his first in twenty years since ''[[Black Tie White Noise]]'' (1993).<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Alan |url=http://www.musicweek.com/businessanalysis/read/official-charts-analysis-davie-bowie-scores-9th-no-1-album/054010 |title=Official Charts Analysis: Davie Bowie scores 9th No.1 album |work=[[Music Week]] |publisher=Intent Media |date=18 March 2013 |accessdate=18 March 2013}} {{subscription required}}</ref> The album fell to number two the following week, selling 35,671 copies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Alan |url=http://www.musicweek.com/businessanalysis/read/official-charts-analysis-timberlake-album-tops-100k-sales-in-one-week/054089 |title=Official Charts Analysis: Timberlake album tops 100k sales in one week |work=Music Week |publisher=Intent Media |date=25 March 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2013}} {{subscription required}}</ref> In its third week, it slipped to number three on sales of 23,157 units.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Alan |url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/official-charts-analysis-let-s-get-ready-to-rhumble-sells-83k/054160 |title=Official Charts Analysis: Let's Get Ready To Rhumble sells 83k |work=Music Week |publisher=Intent Media |date=31 March 2013 |accessdate=12 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208054542/https://www.musicweek.com/news/read/official-charts-analysis-let-s-get-ready-to-rhumble-sells-83k/054160 |archive-date=8 December 2019 |url-status=live }}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the album entered the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] at number two with first-week sales of 85,000 copies, earning Bowie his largest sales week for an album in the [[Nielsen SoundScan]] era,<ref name=\"bb200\">{{cite web |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1552545/bon-jovi-debuts-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-david-bowie-at-no-2 |title=Bon Jovi Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200, David Bowie at No. 2 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=19 March 2013 |accessdate=20 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130322224949/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1552545/bon-jovi-debuts-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-david-bowie-at-no-2 |archive-date=22 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> and also his highest charting album on the ''Billboard'' 200.   The album has sold 208,000 copies in the US as of December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151214223017/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate=14 December 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |website=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref> Elsewhere, ''The Next Day'' topped the charts in several countries, including Belgium, Croatia, Czech Republic, Denmark, Finland, Germany, Ireland, New Zealand, Norway, Poland, Portugal, Sweden and Switzerland,<ref name=\"ultratop\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=The+Next+Day&cat=a |title=David Bowie \u2013 The Next Day |language=French |publisher=Ultratop. Hung Medien |accessdate=15 March 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6FIrofO3T?url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie |archive-date=22 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"cro\"/><ref name=\"cz\"/><ref name=\"ire\"/><ref name=\"pol\"/> while reaching number two in Australia, Austria, Canada, France, Italy, and Spain.<ref name=\"ultratop\"/><ref name=\"can\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-03-30/canadian-albums |title=Canadian Albums : Mar 30, 2013 |work=Billboard |accessdate=27 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328180406/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-03-30/canadian-albums |archive-date=28 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nBowie was insistent that there would be no live performances in support of the album, with Visconti telling the ''[[NME]]'', \"He's fairly adamant he's never gonna perform live again... One of the guys would say, 'Boy, how are we gonna do all this live?' and David said, 'We're not'. He made a point of saying that all the time.\"<ref name=NME13>{{cite web |title=David Bowie producer rules out Bowie live shows |url=http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/68126 |accessdate=11 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113074414/http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/68126 |archive-date=13 January 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Visconti later clarified that he did not say Bowie would never perform live again, only that he \"won't tour for this album\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/Tonuspomus/status/289810690338856960 |title=Twitter / Tonuspomus: I never said Bowie would never ... |publisher=Twitter.com |date=11 January 2013 |accessdate=25 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305045619/https://twitter.com/Tonuspomus/status/289810690338856960 |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Visconti told ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' that Bowie had not ruled out the possibility of several live shows but instead decided to focus on making records.<ref name=OC13/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_lyrics = [[David Bowie]]\n| all_music = Bowie, except where noted\n| title1 = [[The Next Day (song)|The Next Day]]\n| length1 = 3:27\n| title2 = Dirty Boys\n| length2 = 2:58\n| title3 = [[The Stars (Are Out Tonight)]]\n| length3 = 3:56\n| title4 = [[Love Is Lost]]\n| length4 = 3:57\n| title5 = [[Where Are We Now?]]\n| length5 = 4:08\n| title6 = [[Valentine's Day (David Bowie song)|Valentine's Day]]\n| length6 = 3:01\n| title7 = If You Can See Me\n| length7 = 3:15\n| title8 = I'd Rather Be High\n| length8 = 3:53\n| title9 = Boss of Me\n| music9 = Bowie, [[Gerry Leonard]]\n| length9 = 4:09\n| title10 = Dancing Out in Space\n| length10 = 3:24\n| title11 = How Does the Grass Grow?\n| music11 = Bowie, [[Jerry Lordan]]\n| length11 = 4:33\n| title12 = (You Will) Set the World on Fire\n| length12 = 3:30\n| title13 = You Feel So Lonely You Could Die\n| length13 = 4:37\n| title14 = Heat\n| length14 = 4:25\n| total_length = 53:17\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Japanese edition bonus tracks<ref name=sonyjp/>\n| title15 = God Bless the Girl\n| length15 = 4:11\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Deluxe edition bonus tracks<ref name=sonyde/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonymusic.co.jp/Music/International/Arch/SR/DavidBowie/SICP-30127/index.html |title=\u30c7\u30f4\u30a3\u30c3\u30c9\u30fb\u30dc\u30a6\u30a4 : \u30b6\u30fb\u30cd\u30af\u30b9\u30c8\u30fb\u30c7\u30a4\u3000\u30c7\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30b9\u30fb\u30a8\u30c7\u30a3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u3010Blu-spec CD2\u3011 |trans-title=David Bowie: The Next Day (Deluxe Edition) [Blu-spec CD2&#93; |language=Japanese |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment Japan |accessdate=9 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202235803/http://www.sonymusic.co.jp/Music/International/Arch/SR/DavidBowie/SICP-30127/index.html |archive-date=2 December 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| title15 = So She\n| length15 = 2:31\n| title16 = Plan\n| length16 = 2:02\n| title17 = I'll Take You There\n| length17 = 2:41\n| music17 = Bowie, Leonard\n| title18 = God Bless the Girl\n| note18 = Japan only\n| length18 = 4:11\n| total_length = 61:30\n}}\n\n;Japanese edition\n\nThe Japanese edition contains a Blu-spec CD2.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spincds.com/the-next-day-standard-37554 |title=The Next Day (Limited Release Blu-spec 2) |publisher=spincds.com |accessdate=28 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014192642/http://www.spincds.com/the-next-day-standard-37554 |archive-date=14 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n;Vinyl edition\n\n''The Next Day'' was also issued as a double [[LP record|LP]]. It was announced as being released on 25 March 2013 in the UK, but was put back to 1 April, with vinyl customers getting an additional CD copy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B00AYHKOZU|title=The Next Day [VINYL&#93; |publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon.co.uk]] |accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> The vinyl edition included the songs \"So She\", \"Plan\" and \"I'll Take You There\", which were not included on the standard CD release.\n\n===''The Next Day Extra''===\nReleased 4 November 2013, this 3-disc collector's edition includes two CDs and a DVD. The first CD is the original 14-track album. The second is a 10-track CD comprising the deluxe edition bonus tracks \"Plan\", \"I'll Take You There\", and \"So She\", the Japanese exclusive track \"God Bless the Girl\", two remixes, and four new songs (\"Atomica\", \"The Informer\", \"Like a Rocket Man\", and \"Born in a UFO\"). The DVD includes the four promotional music videos (\"Where Are We Now?\", \"The Stars (Are Out Tonight)\", \"The Next Day\", and \"Valentine's Day\").\n\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Atomica\n| length1 = 4:05\n| title2 = Love Is Lost\n| note2 = Hello [[Steve Reich]] Mix by [[James Murphy (electronic musician)|James Murphy]] for the [[DFA Records|DFA]]\n| length2 = 10:24\n| title3 = Plan\n| length3 = 2:02\n| title4 = The Informer\n| length4 = 4:31\n| title6 = Like a Rocket Man\n| length6 = 3:29\n| title7 = Born in a UFO\n| length7 = 3:02\n| title5 = I'd Rather Be High\n| note5 = Venetian Mix\n| length5 = 3:49\n| title8 = I'll Take You There\n| length8 = 2:41\n| music8 = Bowie, Leonard\n| title9 = God Bless the Girl\n| length9 = 4:11\n| title10 = So She\n| length10 = 2:31\n| total_length = 40:45\n}}\n\nIn addition to the physical release there is a 7-track digital EP bundle that excludes the deluxe edition bonus tracks.\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Atomica\n| length1 = 4:05\n| title2 = Love Is Lost\n| note2 = Hello Steve Reich Mix by James Murphy for the DFA\n| length2 = 10:24\n| title3 = The Informer\n| length3 = 4:31\n| title4 = I'd Rather Be High\n| note4 = Venetian Mix\n| length4 = 3:49\n| title5 = Like a Rocket Man\n| length5 = 3:29\n| title6 = Born in a UFO\n| length6 = 3:02\n| title7 = God Bless the Girl\n| length7 = 4:11\n| total_length = 33:31\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of the deluxe edition of ''The Next Day''.<ref name=\"album notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=The Next Day |type=deluxe edition liner notes |others=[[David Bowie]] |publisher=[[Columbia Records]] |year=2013 |id=88765 46192 2}}</ref>\n\n* [[David Bowie]] \u2013 vocals <small>(1\u201315, 17)</small>; production <small>(all tracks)</small>; guitar <small>(1, 16)</small>; string arrangement <small>(1, 3, 15)</small>; acoustic guitar <small>(3, 13\u201315, 17)</small>; keyboards <small>(4, 5, 7, 10, 11, 15\u201317)</small>; percussion <small>(16)</small>\n* [[Zachary Alford]] <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/258947-Zachary-Alford |title=Discogs \u2013 ''Zachary Alford'' \u2013 (profile & discography) |access-date=26 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129164710/https://www.discogs.com/artist/258947-Zachary-Alford |archive-date=29 November 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> \u2013 drums <small>(1\u20135, 7\u201311, 13\u201317)</small>; percussion <small>(7)</small>\n* [[Jonathan Barnbrook]] \u2013 cover design\n* [[Sterling Campbell]] \u2013 drums <small>(6, 12)</small>; tambourine <small>(12)</small>\n* [[Gail Ann Dorsey]] \u2013 bass guitar <small>(1, 3, 4, 10, 11, 13, 14, 17)</small>; backing vocals <small>(3, 7, 9, 11\u201313, 17)</small>\n* Steve Elson \u2013 baritone saxophone <small>(2, 3, 9)</small>; [[clarinet]] <small>(3)</small>\n* Kabir Hermon \u2013 assistant engineering\n* [[Henry Hey]] \u2013 piano <small>(5, 13)</small>\n* Jimmy King \u2013 photography\n* [[Gerry Leonard]] \u2013 guitar <small>(1\u20135, 7\u201315, 17)</small>; keyboards <small>(15)</small>\n* [[Tony Levin]] \u2013 bass guitar <small>(2, 5, 7\u20139)</small>\n* Dave McNair \u2013 mastering\n* [[Mario J. McNulty]] \u2013 engineering\n* Maxim Moston \u2013 strings <small>(1