{"title_page": "Antiquities Act", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name = Antiquities Act\n| fullname = An act for the preservation of American antiquities.\n| nickname =\n| enacted by = 59th\n| effective date = June 8, 1906\n| public law url =\n| cite public law = {{USPL|59|209}}\n| cite statutes at large = {{USStat|34|225}}\n| leghisturl =\n|sections created= {{unbulleted list|{{Usc-title-chap|54|3203}} \u00a7\u00a7\u2009320301 to 320303}}\n| introducedin = House\n| introducedbill = H.R. 11016\n| introducedby = [[John F. Lacey]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]\u2013[[Iowa|IA]])\n| introduceddate = January 9, 1906\n| committees = [[United States House Committee on Public Lands|Public Lands]]\n| passedbody1 = House\n| passeddate1 = June 5, 1906\n| passedvote1 =\n| passedbody2 = Senate\n| passeddate2 = June 7, 1906\n| passedvote2 =\n| agreedbody3 = House\n| agreeddate3 = June 8, 1906\n| agreedvote3 =\n| signedpresident = [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n| signeddate = June 8, 1906\n| SCOTUS cases =''[[Cameron v. United States]]<br>[[Cappaert v. United States]]<br>[[United States v. California]]''\n}}\n[[File:A Yool DevilsTower 04Sep03.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Devils Tower National Monument|Devils Tower]], the first National Monument]]\n\nThe '''Antiquities Act''' of 1906, ({{USPL|59|209}},  {{USStat|34|225}}, {{usc|54|320301|320303}}), is an [[Act of Congress|act]] that was passed by the [[United States Congress]] and signed into law by [[Theodore Roosevelt]] on June 8, 1906. This law gives the President of the United States the authority to, by [[presidential proclamation]], create [[National monument (United States)|national monuments]] from [[public land| federal land]]s to protect significant natural, cultural, or scientific features. The Act has been used more than a hundred times since its passage.\n\n==History==\nThe Antiquities Act was signed into law by President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] during his second term in office. The act resulted from concerns about protecting mostly prehistoric Native American ruins and artifacts -- collectively termed \"[[antiquities]]\" -- on federal lands in the West, such as at [[Chaco Culture National Historical Park|Chaco Canyon, New Mexico]]. Removal of artifacts from these lands by private collectors, \"pot hunters,\" had become a serious problem by the end of the 19th century. In 1902, [[Iowa]] Congressman [[John F. Lacey]], who chaired the House Committee on the Public Lands, traveled to the Southwest with the rising [[anthropology|anthropologist]] [[Edgar Lee Hewett]], to see for himself the extent of the pot hunters' impact.  His findings, supported by an exhaustive report by Hewett to Congress detailing the archaeological resources of the region, provided the necessary impetus for the passage of the legislation.<ref>{{cite AV media | title=The National Parks: America's Best Idea | publisher=Florentine Films | people=Ken Burns}}</ref>\n\nSince the Antiquities Act became law, all but four presidents, Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan, and George H.W. Bush, have chosen to enlarge or dedicate new national monuments.<ref>{{cite web|title=Americian Antiquities Act of 1906|url=https://www.nps.gov/subjects/legal/american-antiquities-act-of-1906.htm|website=National Park Service|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> President Obama established more monuments than any President before him, with 26.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/06/26/obamas-national-monuments-more-than-conservation/82931356/|title=Obama\u2019s national monuments are about more than conservation|last=Korte|first=Gregory|date=|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-18|quote=But Obama's 23 proclamations creating new national monuments are about more than conservation. [''Three more proclaimed after publication of this article'']}}</ref> The previous record was held by President Theodore Roosevelt with 18 monuments.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kraft|first1=Michael|last2=Vig|first2=Norman|title=Environmental Policy New Directions for the Twenty-First Century|date=2017|publisher=Sage|edition=10th}}</ref>  \n\nOn April 26, 2017, President Donald Trump signed an executive order directing a review of the law and its uses.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Merica|first1=Dan|title=Trump order could roll back public lands protections from 3 presidents|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/25/politics/donald-trump-federal-lands-antiquities/index.html|website=CNN|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2019}}\nThe Act was intended to allow the President to set aside certain valuable public natural areas as park and conservation land. The 1906 act stated that it was intended for: \"... the protection of objects of historic and scientific interest.\" These areas are given the title of \"[[U.S. National Monument|National Monuments]].\"  It also allows the President to reserve or accept private lands for that purpose.  The aim is to protect all historic and prehistoric sites on United States federal lands and to prohibit excavation or destruction of these antiquities.  With this act, this can be done much more quickly than going through the Congressional process of creating a [[National Park]].  The Act states that areas of the monuments are to be confined to the smallest area compatible with the proper care and management of the objects to be protected.\n\nThe [[United States Supreme Court]] has repeatedly upheld presidential proclamations under the Antiquities Act, ruling each time that the Act gives the president nearly-unfettered discretion as to the nature of the object to be protected and the size of the area reserved.<ref name=\"Cameron\">[http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/252/450/case.html Cameron v. United States], 252 U.S. 450</ref><ref name=\"Cappaert\">[http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/426/128/case.html Cappaert v. United States], 426 U.S. 128</ref>\n\nSome areas designated as national monuments have later been converted into national parks, or incorporated into existing national parks.\n\nThe first use of the Act protected a large geographic feature&nbsp;\u2013 President Theodore Roosevelt proclaimed [[Devils Tower|Devils Tower National Monument]] on September 24, 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/deto/historyculture/upload/First%2050%20Years.pdf|title=Devils Tower First 50 Years|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=October 11, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531175438/http://www.nps.gov/deto/historyculture/upload/First%2050%20Years.pdf|archivedate=May 31, 2009}}</ref> President Roosevelt also used it to create the Grand Canyon National Monument (now [[Grand Canyon National Park]]).\n\nAt {{convert|583000|sqmi|km2|-4}}, [[Papah\u0101naumoku\u0101kea Marine National Monument]] is the largest protected area proclaimed.<ref>Papah\u0101naumoku\u0101kea protects submerged land.  The largest surface reservation was the proclamation of [[Wrangell-St. Elias National Monument]], {{convert|10950000|acre|km2|-4}}.</ref> The smallest, [[Father Millet Cross|Father Millet Cross National Monument]] (now part of a state park), was a mere {{convert|0.0074|acre|m2|-1}}.<ref name=\"act\">{{Cite journal |title=Antiquites Act: Monument List |url=http://www.nps.gov/history/archeology/sites/antiquities/MonumentsList.htm |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |publisher=National Park Service Archeology Program | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090509202639/http://www.nps.gov/history/archeology/sites/antiquities/MonumentsList.htm| archivedate= May 9, 2009 | url-status= live}}.</ref>\n\nFor any excavation, the Act requires that a permit (Antiquities Permit) be obtained from the Secretary of the department which has jurisdiction over those lands.\n\n==Reduction of powers==\nPresidential powers under the Act have been reduced twice.  The first time followed the unpopular proclamation of [[Jackson Hole National Monument]] in 1943.  The 1950 law that incorporated Jackson Hole into an enlarged [[Grand Teton National Park]] also amended the Antiquities Act, requiring Congressional consent for any future creation or enlargement of National Monuments in [[Wyoming]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/hisnps/npshistory/righter.htm| title=National Monuments to National Parks: The Use of the Antiquities Act of 1906| author=Robert W. Righter| accessdate=May 16, 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060527064514/http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/hisnps/npshistory/righter.htm| archivedate= May 27, 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref> The second time followed [[Jimmy Carter]]'s use of the Act to create {{convert|56|e6acre|km2}} of National Monuments in [[Alaska]].  The [[Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act]] requires Congressional ratification of the use of the Antiquities Act in Alaska for withdrawals of greater than {{convert|5,000|acre|km2}}.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fws.gov/laws/lawsdigest/alaskcn.html| title=Digest of Federal Resource Laws of Interest to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service: Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act of 1980| author=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service| accessdate=May 16, 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060626110319/http://www.fws.gov/laws/lawsdigest/alaskcn.html| archivedate= June 26, 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref> Under the Trump administration, all monuments dedicated after the year 1996 have been called into question. The Trump Administration is possibly looking to modify or even dismantle some of the monuments erected under the 1906 Antiquities Act.<ref name=Vig>{{cite book|last1=Vig|first1=Norman|last2=Kraft|first2=Michael|title=Environmental Policy New Direction for the Twenty-First Century|date=2017|publisher=Sage|page=106-107}}</ref> Although some Presidents have chosen to ignore the tradition of preservation of notable environmental or historic areas, no President to date has undone a predecessor's monument.<ref name=Vig/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of National Monuments of the United States]]\n* [[Timeline of environmental events]]\n* [[National Park Service]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisourcepar|An Act for the Preservation of American Antiquities}}\n{{Commons category|National Monuments of the United States}}\n* [http://www.nps.gov/archeology/SITES/Antiquities/docs/2007RSellars-VeryLargeArray-AntiqActMEVENPS.pdf Richard West Sellars, \"A Very Large Array: Early Federal Historic Preservation--The Antiquities Act, Mesa Verde, and the National Park Service Act\"(background and legislative history) published by the University of New Mexico School of Law, 2007]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/archeology/sites/antiquities/monumentslist.htm Chronological list of uses of the Antiquities Act and related actions] from NPS\n* [http://www.cr.nps.gov/archeology/pubs/lee/ ''The Story of the Antiquities Act'', by Ronald F. Lee]\n*[https://www.nps.gov/history/archeology/sites/antiquities/ Antiquities Act 1906\u20132006]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/history/local-law/anti1906.htm The National Park Service]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070809053457/http://www.theodore-roosevelt.com/trantiqueact.html Almanac of Theodore Roosevelt]\n* [http://www.archaeology.org/online/features/act1906/act.html Archeology.org]\n* [http://www.uapress.arizona.edu/Books/bid1649.htm/ ''The Antiquities Act: A Century of American Archaeology, Historic Preservation, and Nature Conservation'', ed. by David Harmon, Frank P. McManamon, and Dwight T. Pitcaithley]\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=90631198 The Highs and Lows of the Antiquities Act]\n\n{{US Environmental law}}\n{{Theodore Roosevelt}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1906 in law]]\n[[Category:1906 in the environment]]\n[[Category:1906 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Progressive Era in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States federal environmental legislation]]\n[[Category:United States federal public land legislation]]\n[[Category:National Park Service]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox U.S. legislation\n| name = Antiquities Act\n| fullname = An act for the preservation of American antiquities.\n| nickname =\n| enacted by = 59th\n| effective date = June 8, 1906\n| public law url =\n| cite public law = {{USPL|59|209}}\n| cite statutes at large = {{USStat|34|225}}\n| leghisturl =\n|sections created= {{unbulleted list|{{Usc-title-chap|54|3203}} \u00a7\u00a7\u2009320301 to 320303}}\n| introducedin = House\n| introducedbill = H.R. 11016\n| introducedby = [[John F. Lacey]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]\u2013[[Iowa|IA]])\n| introduceddate = January 9, 1906\n| committees = [[United States House Committee on Public Lands|Public Lands]]\n| passedbody1 = House\n| passeddate1 = June 5, 1906\n| passedvote1 =\n| passedbody2 = Senate\n| passeddate2 = June 7, 1906\n| passedvote2 =\n| agreedbody3 = House\n| agreeddate3 = June 8, 1906\n| agreedvote3 =\n| signedpresident = [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n| signeddate = June 8, 1906\n| SCOTUS cases =''[[Cameron v. United States]]<br>[[Cappaert v. United States]]<br>[[United States v. California]]''\n}}\n[[File:A Yool DevilsTower 04Sep03.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Devils Tower National Monument|Devils Tower]], the first National Monument]]\n\nThe '''Antiquities Act''' of 1906, ({{USPL|59|209}},  {{USStat|34|225}}, {{usc|54|320301|320303}}), is an [[Act of Congress|act]] that was passed by the [[United States Congress]] and signed into law by [[Theodore Roosevelt]] on June 8, 1906. This law gives the President of the United States the authority to, by [[presidential proclamation]], create [[National monument (United States)|national monuments]] from [[public land| federal land]]s to protect significant natural, cultural, or scientific features. The Act has been used more than a hundred times since its passage.\n\n==History==\nThe Antiquities Act was signed into law by President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] during his second term in office. The act resulted from concerns about protecting mostly prehistoric Native American ruins and artifacts--collectively termed \"[[antiquities]]\"--on federal lands in the West, such as at [[Chaco Culture National Historical Park|Chaco Canyon, New Mexico]]. Removal of artifacts from these lands by private collectors, \"pot hunters,\" had become a serious problem by the end of the 19th century. In 1902, [[Iowa]] Congressman [[John F. Lacey]], who chaired the House Committee on the Public Lands, traveled to the Southwest with the rising [[anthropology|anthropologist]] [[Edgar Lee Hewett]], to see for himself the extent of the pot hunters' impact.  His findings, supported by an exhaustive report by Hewett to Congress detailing the archaeological resources of the region, provided the necessary impetus for the passage of the legislation.<ref>{{cite AV media | title=The National Parks: America's Best Idea | publisher=Florentine Films | people=Ken Burns}}</ref>\n\nSince the Antiquities Act became law, all but four presidents, Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan, and George H.W. Bush, have chosen to enlarge or dedicate new national monuments.<ref>{{cite web|title=Americian Antiquities Act of 1906|url=https://www.nps.gov/subjects/legal/american-antiquities-act-of-1906.htm|website=National Park Service|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> President Obama established more monuments than any President before him, with 26.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/06/26/obamas-national-monuments-more-than-conservation/82931356/|title=Obama\u2019s national monuments are about more than conservation|last=Korte|first=Gregory|date=|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-18|quote=But Obama's 23 proclamations creating new national monuments are about more than conservation. [''Three more proclaimed after publication of this article'']}}</ref> The previous record was held by President Theodore Roosevelt with 18 monuments.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kraft|first1=Michael|last2=Vig|first2=Norman|title=Environmental Policy New Directions for the Twenty-First Century|date=2017|publisher=Sage|edition=10th}}</ref>  \n\nOn April 26, 2017, President Donald Trump signed an executive order directing a review of the law and its uses.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Merica|first1=Dan|title=Trump order could roll back public lands protections from 3 presidents|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/25/politics/donald-trump-federal-lands-antiquities/index.html|website=CNN|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2019}}\nThe Act was intended to allow the President to set aside certain valuable public natural areas as park and conservation land. The 1906 act stated that it was intended for: \"... the protection of objects of historic and scientific interest.\" These areas are given the title of \"[[U.S. National Monument|National Monuments]].\"  It also allows the President to reserve or accept private lands for that purpose.  The aim is to protect all historic and prehistoric sites on United States federal lands and to prohibit excavation or destruction of these antiquities.  With this act, this can be done much more quickly than going through the Congressional process of creating a [[National Park]].  The Act states that areas of the monuments are to be confined to the smallest area compatible with the proper care and management of the objects to be protected.\n\nThe [[United States Supreme Court]] has repeatedly upheld presidential proclamations under the Antiquities Act, ruling each time that the Act gives the president nearly-unfettered discretion as to the nature of the object to be protected and the size of the area reserved.<ref name=\"Cameron\">[http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/252/450/case.html Cameron v. United States], 252 U.S. 450</ref><ref name=\"Cappaert\">[http://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/426/128/case.html Cappaert v. United States], 426 U.S. 128</ref>\n\nSome areas designated as national monuments have later been converted into national parks, or incorporated into existing national parks.\n\nThe first use of the Act protected a large geographic feature&nbsp;\u2013 President Theodore Roosevelt proclaimed [[Devils Tower|Devils Tower National Monument]] on September 24, 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/deto/historyculture/upload/First%2050%20Years.pdf|title=Devils Tower First 50 Years|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=October 11, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531175438/http://www.nps.gov/deto/historyculture/upload/First%2050%20Years.pdf|archivedate=May 31, 2009}}</ref> President Roosevelt also used it to create the Grand Canyon National Monument (now [[Grand Canyon National Park]]).\n\nAt {{convert|583000|sqmi|km2|-4}}, [[Papah\u0101naumoku\u0101kea Marine National Monument]] is the largest protected area proclaimed.<ref>Papah\u0101naumoku\u0101kea protects submerged land.  The largest surface reservation was the proclamation of [[Wrangell-St. Elias National Monument]], {{convert|10950000|acre|km2|-4}}.</ref> The smallest, [[Father Millet Cross|Father Millet Cross National Monument]] (now part of a state park), was a mere {{convert|0.0074|acre|m2|-1}}.<ref name=\"act\">{{Cite journal |title=Antiquites Act: Monument List |url=http://www.nps.gov/history/archeology/sites/antiquities/MonumentsList.htm |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |publisher=National Park Service Archeology Program | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090509202639/http://www.nps.gov/history/archeology/sites/antiquities/MonumentsList.htm| archivedate= May 9, 2009 | url-status= live}}.</ref>\n\nFor any excavation, the Act requires that a permit (Antiquities Permit) be obtained from the Secretary of the department which has jurisdiction over those lands.\n\n==Reduction of powers==\nPresidential powers under the Act have been reduced twice.  The first time followed the unpopular proclamation of [[Jackson Hole National Monument]] in 1943.  The 1950 law that incorporated Jackson Hole into an enlarged [[Grand Teton National Park]] also amended the Antiquities Act, requiring Congressional consent for any future creation or enlargement of National Monuments in [[Wyoming]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/hisnps/npshistory/righter.htm| title=National Monuments to National Parks: The Use of the Antiquities Act of 1906| author=Robert W. Righter| accessdate=May 16, 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060527064514/http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/hisnps/npshistory/righter.htm| archivedate= May 27, 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref> The second time followed [[Jimmy Carter]]'s use of the Act to create {{convert|56|e6acre|km2}} of National Monuments in [[Alaska]].  The [[Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act]] requires Congressional ratification of the use of the Antiquities Act in Alaska for withdrawals of greater than {{convert|5,000|acre|km2}}.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fws.gov/laws/lawsdigest/alaskcn.html| title=Digest of Federal Resource Laws of Interest to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service: Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act of 1980| author=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service| accessdate=May 16, 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060626110319/http://www.fws.gov/laws/lawsdigest/alaskcn.html| archivedate= June 26, 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref> Under the Trump administration, all monuments dedicated after the year 1996 have been called into question. The Trump Administration is possibly looking to modify or even dismantle some of the monuments erected under the 1906 Antiquities Act.<ref name=Vig>{{cite book|last1=Vig|first1=Norman|last2=Kraft|first2=Michael|title=Environmental Policy New Direction for the Twenty-First Century|date=2017|publisher=Sage|page=106-107}}</ref> Although some Presidents have chosen to ignore the tradition of preservation of notable environmental or historic areas, no President to date has undone a predecessor's monument.<ref name=Vig/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of National Monuments of the United States]]\n* [[Timeline of environmental events]]\n* [[National Park Service]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisourcepar|An Act for the Preservation of American Antiquities}}\n{{Commons category|National Monuments of the United States}}\n* [http://www.nps.gov/archeology/SITES/Antiquities/docs/2007RSellars-VeryLargeArray-AntiqActMEVENPS.pdf Richard West Sellars, \"A Very Large Array: Early Federal Historic Preservation--The Antiquities Act, Mesa Verde, and the National Park Service Act\"(background and legislative history) published by the University of New Mexico School of Law, 2007]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/archeology/sites/antiquities/monumentslist.htm Chronological list of uses of the Antiquities Act and related actions] from NPS\n* [http://www.cr.nps.gov/archeology/pubs/lee/ ''The Story of the Antiquities Act'', by Ronald F. Lee]\n*[https://www.nps.gov/history/archeology/sites/antiquities/ Antiquities Act 1906\u20132006]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/history/local-law/anti1906.htm The National Park Service]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070809053457/http://www.theodore-roosevelt.com/trantiqueact.html Almanac of Theodore Roosevelt]\n* [http://www.archaeology.org/online/features/act1906/act.html Archeology.org]\n* [http://www.uapress.arizona.edu/Books/bid1649.htm/ ''The Antiquities Act: A Century of American Archaeology, Historic Preservation, and Nature Conservation'', ed. by David Harmon, Frank P. McManamon, and Dwight T. Pitcaithley]\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=90631198 The Highs and Lows of the Antiquities Act]\n\n{{US Environmental law}}\n{{Theodore Roosevelt}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1906 in law]]\n[[Category:1906 in the environment]]\n[[Category:1906 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Progressive Era in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States federal environmental legislation]]\n[[Category:United States federal public land legislation]]\n[[Category:National Park Service]]\n", "name_user": "Devotional-Living", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiquities_Act"}
